ernational agencies, local expatriates, US media, Bangladeshi immigrants in the United States, survivor-activists, and local women's organizations engage the pragmatics and the transnational rhetoric of empowerment, rescue, and rehabilitation. Grounded in careful ethnographic work, oral history, and theoretical and filmic analysis, Transnationalism Reversed makes a significant contribution to conversations around gendered violence, transnational feminist praxis, and the politics of organizing—particularly around NGOs—in the global South.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFeminism -- Bangladesh. 0aFeminismzBangladesh. 0aWomen -- Bangladesh -- Social conditions. 0aWomen -- Violence against -- Bangladesh. 0aWomenxViolence againstzBangladesh. 0aWomenzBangladeshxSocial conditions. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Feminist. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : International Organizations. 4aSociology : Violence. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438437538423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438437538/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles